'''Bernal de Foix, 1st Count of Medinaceli''' ({{lang-es|[[Don (honorific)|Mosén]] Bernardo de Bearne y Foix, primer conde de Medinaceli}}; d. 1381), also known as "the Bastard of Bearn",<ref name="cruel"/> was a military officer in the [[Crown of Castile]], a region that is now part of [[Spain]].
==Life and career== Bernal de Foix was an [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] son of [[Gaston III de Foix]], the 11th [[Count of Foix]]. He was invested as the first [[Duke of Medinaceli|Count of Medinaceli]] in 1368, and he married Doña [[Isabel de la Cerda]] in 1370. Isabel, the widow of [[Ruy Pérez Ponce de León]], was the granddaughter of [[Alfonso de la Cerda]], a grandson of King [[Alfonso X of Castile]]. She was granted large [[Estate (land)|estates]] on the condition that she relinquish all claims to the Crown of Castile for herself and her heirs.<ref name="cruel">{{cite book | title = The History of Peter the Cruel, King of Castile and Leon. With additional notes | last = Mérimée | first = Prosper | volume = 1 | pages = 307–308 | location = London | publisher = Richard Bentley | year = 1849 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=VKNFAAAAIAAJ&dq=the%20history%20of%20peter%20the%20cruel&pg=RA1-PA307#v=onepage&q=bernal%20de%20foix&f=false | accessdate = 2010-10-17 | oclc = 13136669 }} (Translation of ''Histoire de Don Pèdre I<sup>er</sup>, Roi de Castille'')</ref>
He took the side of royal bastard [[Henry II of Castile|Henry of Trastámara]] against Henry's legitimate half-brother, King [[Peter of Castile]], during the [[Castilian Civil War]]. He commanded a troop of Castilians under Henry.<ref name="cruel"/> He chose to stay in Castile when Henry killed King Peter at the Castle of Montiel in March 1369.
The Count of Medinaceli donated property to his wife on 15 October 1370.<ref>{{MLCC |warning=1 |url=http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/TOULOUSE%20NOBILITY.htm | title = Toulouse, Nobility | title-date = 2010-03-16 |date=October 2010}}</ref> The family later had extensive estates in the Spanish provinces of [[Province of Soria|Soria]] and [[Province of Guadalajara|Guadalajara]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://collections.glasgowmuseums.com/starobject.html?oid=81993 | title = Milk-glass goblet | work = Glasgow Museums | publisher = Glasgow Museums | accessdate = 2010-10-17 }}</ref>
==Issue== He and his wife had two children: *Gastón (1371–1404), succeeded his father as 2nd Count of Medinaceli *María (d. 1381), died in childhood
